		  <td class="forum_boardrow1" style="border-width: 0px 1px 1px 1px;" valign="top"><div id="message31079073">Pretty much agreeing here. The main characters in Berserk's Golden Age arc felt really mature and developed despite not being likable at times. So, for instance, Griffith I'd say is one of my favourite villains (I want to kill him, so that's probably good!) in anime. Guts, though inspiring, has his moments of vehement emotions that make me feel unease, and yet there's something so tranquil about his falsely heroic character. Casca gets development, but her memories become an ace in the hole (which is bound to be holed there for awhile) after that graphic upbringing of the demon... by-blow... thing. <br />
<br />
Needless to say, most side characters, whose stories were once engaging, lose some fuel after the Golden Age arc, too. Someone please tell Miura to <span style="text-decoration:line-through;">kill<!--strike--></span> write off that little fairy elves thing. Goodness' sake.<br />
<br />
Anyway, Berserk is basically Naruto without the fanbois. [it's never gonna finish]</div><div class="postActions"></div></td>
